00:08:08.919 --> 00:08:13.119
and Heinz not being obligated to pay many
of the debts the company held, he voluntarily

00:08:13.119 --> 00:08:19.340
chose to do so anyways, as he felt morally
obligated, though this took some time.

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:23.020
• The Long Depression started innocently
enough when Germany decided to get rid of

00:08:23.020 --> 00:08:28.050
silver as the backing material for their money
in 1871. This decreased the value of silver

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:32.709
and particularly hurt certain U.S. businesses
who mined a significant amount of the world’s

00:08:32.709 --> 00:08:37.269
silver. The U.S. then decided to follow suit
and stop backing its money with gold and silver

00:08:37.269 --> 00:08:42.390
and decided to just go with gold (as a part
of the Coinage Act of 1873). This even more

00:08:42.390 --> 00:08:47.110
drastically killed the price of silver and
subsequently raised interest rates significantly.

00:08:47.110 --> 00:08:50.370
Businesses and farmers, who typically kept
a fair amount of debt at times, were caught

00:08:50.370 --> 00:08:55.209
off guard by this sudden shift and rise of
interest rates. Investors then got in on the

00:08:55.209 --> 00:08:59.519
panic and stopped wanting to invest in endeavors
that would tie up funds for long periods of

00:08:59.519 --> 00:09:03.509
time, preferring to keep a lot of money on
hand. In modern times, the housing bubble

00:09:03.509 --> 00:09:07.740
contributed to our “little depression”;
back then it was a giant railroading bubble

00:09:07.740 --> 00:09:12.370
that burst around this same time as the silver
fiasco. This had a drastic effect on the nation

00:09:12.370 --> 00:09:16.290
because railroad companies of the day were
(combined) the second largest employer in

00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:20.500
the U.S. after agriculture. Finally, one of
the larger banks in the country, Jay Cooke

00:09:20.500 --> 00:09:25.600
&amp; Company, went under in 1873 largely due
to being too heavily invested in railroads

00:09:25.600 --> 00:09:29.910
and it was all downhill from there with bank
after bank suffering the same fate as Jay

00:09:29.910 --> 00:09:44.779
Cooke &amp; Company. This first “Great Depression”
also hit most of Europe just as hard as the

00:09:44.779 --> 00:09:49.129
U.S.

